value.0: From the neck down, this figure very much looks like a human, garbed in fine, tailored clothes - though its dull, rubbery black skin belies the fact that this creature has very inhuman origins. Its head, however, is the biggest giveaway. It is completely hairless, and devoid of anything resembling eyes, with a too-large mouth drawn back in an impossibly-wide fiendish grin, revealing a full set of jagged, black teeth.

Draocht na matin is the trusted blade forged by Lanerd of the Mc Stone-fists clan. 

It is forged in the ancient tradition of the Mc Stone-fists clan where one replaces the blade he was given by his caretakers (usually the father). One does this as a token to prove one is ready to shake off the younger years, and possibly start a family of his own. The symbolism of this is that before going through this ritual one is still under the instructions and guidance of elders, and after this one is fully ready for his own path. 

This particular blade is named Draocht na matin to honor the way Lanerd learned where and how his own path leads. The blade is mainly made out of Mithril but has 2 edges and inlay of Adamantine for adding strength to the blade. The hilt is wrapped in wyvern leather, and the pommel is set with a large Ruby.

Along the blade, visible text is written in the Terran dialect using the Dethek runes: "Onir don clan, onir do bhs maith".

On the hilt of the blade is a small mark pressed into the metal of a stone rock with a stag's head set into it.

This plain silver band has been worn down to reduce the shimmering of the metal's natural luster. The centerpiece of the ring is a small heart-shaped sapphire containing a swirling red mist. Like the fey creature bearing this ring's namesake, the wearer gains the ability to breathe under water as long as they wear it.

A fashionable corset-backed lady's waistcoat hand-stitched from leather panels. Designed to offer a surprising amount of protection whilst not sacrificing freedom of movement of the wearer. The inner panels are supple and soft, and the outer panels have been polished to a dull luster. Small relief prints of moonshae knots line the lapel of the vest, while silver clips and a tie chain offer a slightly refined flair. The initials "M. V." can be found monogrammed to the inside panels. The waistcoat has a vaguely enchanted aura of the illusion spell school about it. Occasionally, hues of the leather shift as the wearer moves about, perhaps aiding in some form of camouflage.

This item is tied to the character (untradable) and should not be found unequipped, as it is a mythalled ring of the purple dragon to which a warlock passive features was added onto. In case of a class-change, the DC paid for this will not be refund and the item will be taken away if the conditions are not met anymore (lvl 19 warlock).
This ring is meant only for emulating the passive DR of the Warlock class, while Saya is not wearing the Warlock Tied Ring.

A Spider carved of obsidian, inlaid with rubies as its eyes and the hourglass on its abdomen, it is trimmed with wire - Gold for the Ilharess, Gold and Silver twined for the Ilharn, and Silver for the rest of the Qu'ellar. This insignia marks the bearer as a member of Qu'ellar Vilrath of Nec'perya, formerly of Sschindylryn, a Noble Drow house.

You see a large, flawless ruby with intricate runes inscribed on top. When rubbed against a weapon and the command word pronounced it produces a magical flame onto the weapon. If inspected with a magnifying glass, a initials NZ can be seen, standing for Naltyrr Zau'tar, the originator of the runes.

While seemingly normal on a outside glance, it is upon inspecting the inside of this head-piece, does it truly earns the title of a 'contraption'; it's design is far from the typical equipment sported by many warriors around Toril, or even like the magical equipment donned by the adventuring class.

Built into the upper-section of the piece, covering the eyes, are a pair of rubes lenses, the frames holding them connected to a lever mechanism allowing it to be positioned in front of the wearer's eyes and above. The lenses hold an enchantment to reveal magical signatures to its wearer, no doubt serving as one of the core functions of this equipment.

The lower half is a different invention itself. A filtered device covers the nose and mouth, supported by the enchantments commonly seen on a Crab Helmet, it seems this equipment was made to be used in all fields, even deep under the sea.

Additional Enchantment:
Arcane Sight (permanent enchantment/PnP ability, PnP rules apply)

The Zau'tar House Insignia is an ornate shadesteel brooch decorated with an overlying silver filligree; inset in a line along the length of the brooch are two black sapphires with a larger, deep burgundy-colored garnet centered between them. A series of miniature black pearls surround each of the three gemstones, with slightly larger pearls situated along the border of the brooch like compass points.

The three gemstones are enchanted in such a way that the bearer may call upon the spells held within them. The garnet may be used to summon a displacer beast up to five times per day, while the sapphires can be used to cast Ultravision and Displacement three times per day each.

Being the wicked, unwieldy weapons they are, Warforged scythes, diremaces, and double bladed swords are more likely to end up glimmering dully above a mantelpiece than glistening with blood on the field of battle. But for a few powerful individuals that can manage to handle one of these flashy weapons, they might find that cleaving off body parts goes quite a deal easier than normal.

OOC: Bonded to Andre'us Larson

Forged from the metal of a legendary quarter staff, the bones of the late Nveryiothavraex, father of Beliixech, Charnalaxz, and Illunamaeryx, Blessed by Bahamut to dispose of Tiamat's spawn, it brims with Lesser Dragonbane properties.

A masterfully crafted greataxe, forged in the style of the famed Uthgardt tribes. Its blades edges have a potent En hantment which strikes fear into the hearts it draws blood from, and after a suitable amount of terror has been wrought upon the wielders foes, it fills them with uncontrollable fury to match with the barbarians of the Uthgardt themselves. It glows with the fierce light when in the presence of the Uthgarsts greatest foes, the orcs, though its honed edges are potent against any enemy.

A tiny symbol of a swirling wind discreetly shows on the shaft, likely the trademark of its creator.
